      <header class="entry-header"> 
       <h1 class="entry-title">EarthScope Symposium and Reception</h1> 
      </header> 
      <div class="entry-summary"> 
       <p>Download the presentations from all events below. All content for the below presentations belong to the authors, and author consent is required to publish or resuse any portion of content:</p> 
       <p>Presentations from Senate and House Briefings:<br> <a href="/assets/uploads/misc/20140514_EarthScope_Briefing_Arrowsmith_shorter2.pptx">EarthScope Overview (Ramon Arrowsmith)</a><br> <a href="/assets/uploads/misc/EarthScope_briefings_simons.pptx">EarthScope: Past, Present and Future (Mark Simons)</a><br> <a href="/assets/uploads/misc/ES_House_R+D_final.pptx">EarthScope: A Decade of Discovery and Science in the Public Interest (Jeffrey T. Freymueller)</a></p> 
       <p>Presentations from EarthScope Symposium:<br> <a href="/assets/uploads/misc/1300_USArray_slides_for_Bob_Detrick.pptx">Welcome (Robert S. Detrick)</a><br> <a href="/assets/uploads/misc/1325_EarthScope_Symposium_Arrowsmith_Final.pptx">EarthScope Facility Overview (Ramon Arrowsmith)</a><br> <a href="/assets/uploads/misc/1340_ES_Decadal_Freymueller.pptx">EarthScope Science Overview (Jeffrey T. Freymueller)</a><br> <a href="/assets/uploads/misc/1410_EarthScope10yr_PBO_simons.pptx">Plate Boundary Observatory (Mark Simons)</a><br> <a href="/assets/uploads/misc/1440_Gilbert_geo_earthqauke_comp.pptx">USArray Science Overview (Hersh Gilbert)</a><br> <a href="/assets/uploads/misc/1440_msmiller_es_science_may15_FINAL.pptx">USArray Science Overview (Meghan S. Miller)</a><br> <a href="/assets/uploads/misc/1540_SavageEarthscopeTalk2014_final.pptx">San Andreas Fault Observatory at Depth Science Overview (Heather Savage)</a><br> <a href="/assets/uploads/misc/1610_Semken_ESEnO_Decade2014.pptx">Education and Outreach of EarthScope (Steven Semken)</a></p> 
       <h3 style="text-align: center;">Celebrating a Decade of Geoscience Accomplishments</h3> 
       <p>In 2004, the epic undertaking of the EarthScope program, funded by the National Science Foundation (NSF), became a reality.&nbsp; Over the next ten years, revolutionary scientific results have helped researchers better understand the geologic structure and evolution of North America, the dynamics of the North American-Pacific plate boundary, and the processes that drive earthquakes and volcanoes. This past May, several hundred individuals, representing a broad cross-section of EarthScope researchers, educators, leaders, and stakeholders, gathered in Washington, DC to celebrate a decade of accomplishment by the EarthScope program.</p> 
       <p>The two-day event included briefings to members of the House and Senate and a Decade Symposium that was hosted at the American Association for the Advancement of Science Building.</p> 
       <p>House and Senate briefings included presentations on the EarthScope Program overall, and specific information on the EarthScope facilities (Plate Boundary Observatory, USArray, and SAFOD) from Ramon Arrowsmith, William Leith (U.S. Geological Survey), Rowena Lohman (Cornell), Meghan S. Miller (USC), and Mark Simons (Caltech).&nbsp; Various Congressional and Senate staff members attended these presentations.</p> 
       <p>The Decade Symposium began with plenary presentations on the evolution of the EarthScope facilities along with their current status, scientific accomplishments made possible by the collaborative nature of EarthScope, and on EarthScope’s extensive Education and Outreach activities. Presenters included M. Meghan Miller (UNAVCO), Robert Detrick (IRIS), Roger Wakimoto (NSF), Ramon Arrowsmith and Steven Semken (ESNO at ASU), Jeffrey Freymueller (Univ. Alaska-Fairbanks), Mark Simons, Meghan S. Miller, Hersh Gilbert (Purdue), and Heather Savage (Lamont-Doherty Earth Observatory).</p> 
       <p>The plenary talks were followed by a panel discussion on the Broader Impacts, Policy, and Future of EarthScope; featuring representatives of NSF (Greg Anderson), National Aeronautics and Space Administration (John LaBrecque), National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (Julianna Blackwell and Iffikhar Jamil), and the U. S. Geological Survey. (William Leith). Over 300 people attended the talks and the panel discussion.&nbsp; The Decade Symposium also featured an exhibit hall where the EarthScope National Office, IRIS, UNAVCO, and SAFOD displayed geoscientific research equipment and multimedia exhibits from the USArray, the Plate Boundary Observatory, and a San Andreas core replica.</p> 
       <p>The Decade Symposium concluded with a reception that featured congratulatory and encouraging remarks from Dr. Cora Marrett, the Director of NSF.</p> 
